<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="249" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,757,464,1097]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,311,464,488]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Observations:</emphasis>
Typical medusa of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hartlaub" authorityYear="1914" box="[643,713,465,488]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Pandeidae" genus="Merga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="13" pageNumber="249" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[643,713,465,488]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Merga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, up to 
<quantity box="[183,262,497,521]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="13" pageNumber="249" unit="mm" value="12.0">12 mm</quantity>
high, characteristic light pink-purple colour of manubrium and tentacles (
<figureCitation box="[517,593,528,552]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="12.[151,186,1867,1889]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,258,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-7@12.[151,1436,258,1828]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Fig. 6. Merga violacea. (A-D) Specimen BFLA4006, bell height 12 mm. (A) Lateral view of whole animal, note that the bell is somewhat contracted and more elongate than normal. (B) Bell margin seen from oral, note the flat abaxial spurs above some of the tentacle bulbs (arrow). (C) Lateral view of stomach. (D) Bell margin, note rudimentary bulbs with short tentacle stumps. (E) Lateral view of younger animal observed 30-Jun-2018, size approximately 7 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5639954" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5639954/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
A-E), without apical process but when fully grown with a thick apical jelly, shallow subumbrellar pockets present. Manubrium about half the height of subumbrella, very wide, connected for about half its length along the radial canals; stomach base and mouth cruciform, mouth rim slightly folded. Gonads on interradial surfaces of stomach, thin, smooth and not folded. Four radial canals broad, connected to stomach in its upper parts as mesenteries. Eight long, tapering tentacles, base laterally compressed and clasping bell margin, may be continued on exumbrella as an atypical, flat, abaxial spur (
<figureCitation box="[307,397,912,936]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="12.[151,186,1867,1889]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,258,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-7@12.[151,1436,258,1828]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Fig. 6. Merga violacea. (A-D) Specimen BFLA4006, bell height 12 mm. (A) Lateral view of whole animal, note that the bell is somewhat contracted and more elongate than normal. (B) Bell margin seen from oral, note the flat abaxial spurs above some of the tentacle bulbs (arrow). (C) Lateral view of stomach. (D) Bell margin, note rudimentary bulbs with short tentacle stumps. (E) Lateral view of younger animal observed 30-Jun-2018, size approximately 7 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5639954" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5639954/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
); large red abaxial ocellus near abaxial end of bulb. Rarely also 9 tentacles observed. Alternating with the tentacles 2-5 small bulbs (max. total 34) with a short, blunt tentacle stump, all the same size and also with a red ocellus. Usually with brown pigment dots in the stomach wall (
<figureCitation box="[519,633,1072,1097]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="12.[151,186,1867,1889]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,258,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-7@12.[151,1436,258,1828]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Fig. 6. Merga violacea. (A-D) Specimen BFLA4006, bell height 12 mm. (A) Lateral view of whole animal, note that the bell is somewhat contracted and more elongate than normal. (B) Bell margin seen from oral, note the flat abaxial spurs above some of the tentacle bulbs (arrow). (C) Lateral view of stomach. (D) Bell margin, note rudimentary bulbs with short tentacle stumps. (E) Lateral view of younger animal observed 30-Jun-2018, size approximately 7 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5639954" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5639954/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Fig. 6C, E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="249" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,755,1119,1176]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,301,1119,1143]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Distribution:</emphasis>
Circumglobal in tropical to subtropical waters (
<bibRefCitation author="Schuchert" box="[235,414,1152,1176]" firstAuthor="Schuchert" pageId="13" pageNumber="249" pagination="195 - 396" refId="ref74456" refString="Schuchert P. 2007. The European athecate hydroids and their medusae (Hydrozoa, Cnidaria): Filifera Part 2. Revue suisse de Zoologie 114 (2): 195 - 396." type="journal article" year="2007">Schuchert, 2007</bibRefCitation>
). 
<typeStatus box="[431,484,1152,1176]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Type</typeStatus>
locality: 
<collectingCountry box="[585,708,1152,1176]" name="Fiji" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Fiji Islands</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="249" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,756,1198,1415]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,264,1198,1223]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">16S Data:</emphasis>
The partial 16S gene sequence (
<accessionNumber box="[616,749,1199,1223]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/MW528650" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">MW528650</accessionNumber>
) obtained was used to search for similar sequences in GenBank using the blastn function. Other similar sequences found were as expected of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1879" box="[561,671,1295,1319]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Pandeidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="13" pageNumber="249" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="family">Pandeidae</taxonomicName>
species but had only identities below 89%. The similarities with the 
<taxonomicName box="[249,458,1359,1383]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Pandeidae" genus="Pandeopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="13" pageNumber="249" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[249,372,1359,1383]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Pandeopsis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
described below were also relatively low (&lt;86%, see also 
<figureCitation box="[482,546,1391,1415]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[151,186,1937,1959]" captionTargetId="graphics-7@15.[50,1262,520,1548]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 8. 16S rRNA maximum likelihood phylogenetic tree of Pandeidae species obtained with PhyML (GTR+G+I model) and based" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5710580" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5710580/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="249" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,756,1438,2070]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,265,1438,1462]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Remarks:</emphasis>
The species has recently been redescribed and discussed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Schuchert" box="[360,555,1470,1494]" firstAuthor="Schuchert" pageId="13" pageNumber="249" pagination="195 - 396" refId="ref74456" refString="Schuchert P. 2007. The European athecate hydroids and their medusae (Hydrozoa, Cnidaria): Filifera Part 2. Revue suisse de Zoologie 114 (2): 195 - 396." type="journal article" year="2007">Schuchert (2007)</bibRefCitation>
, but the problem with the 
<typeStatus box="[262,308,1502,1526]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">type</typeStatus>
locality remains unresolved. No 
<typeStatus box="[709,755,1502,1526]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">type</typeStatus>
material could be located in the Harvard Museum of Zoology (A. Baldinger, pers. com. 
<date box="[572,695,1566,1590]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249" value="2019-06">June 2019</date>
), the museum Agassiz and Mayer were associated with.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,756,1438,2070]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">
<bibRefCitation author="Agassiz &amp; Mayer" box="[151,429,1630,1654]" firstAuthor="Agassiz" pageId="13" pageNumber="249" pagination="157 - 189" refId="ref64040" refString="Agassiz A., Mayer A. G. 1899. Acalephs from the Fiji Islands. Bulletin of the Museum of comparative Zoology of Harvard College 32 (9): 157 - 189, pls 1 - 17." type="journal article" year="1899">Agassiz &amp; Mayer (1899)</bibRefCitation>
introduced the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Agassiz &amp; Mayer" authorityYear="1899" class="Hydrozoa" family="Pandeidae" genus="Pandea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="13" pageNumber="249" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="violacea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Pandea violacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in a paper reporting on medusae collected in the 
<collectingCountry box="[151,188,1694,1718]" name="Fiji" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Fiji</collectingCountry>
archipelago. 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:D0118A7C5B070019FC45F990FC2D79B9:5D676DB15B010019FE82F908FEB87E95" box="[333,355,1694,1717]" country="Fiji" county="Archipelago" municipality="Notwithstanding" name="In" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">In</location>
the description – no figure was given – they state that they have also found indistinguishable medusae at the 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:D0118A7C5B070019FC45F990FC2D79B9:5D676DB15B010019FEF5F948FEB87ED6" box="[314,355,1758,1782]" country="Fiji" county="Archipelago" municipality="Notwithstanding" name="Dry" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Dry</location>
Tortugas 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:D0118A7C5B070019FC45F990FC2D79B9:5D676DB15B010019FE03F948FDC37ED6" box="[460,536,1758,1782]" country="Fiji" county="Archipelago" municipality="Notwithstanding" name="Islands" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Islands</location>
which they intended to illustrate in a subsequent publication. 
<collectingMunicipality box="[571,752,1790,1814]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Notwithstanding</collectingMunicipality>
, the paper dealt with specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[536,573,1822,1846]" name="Fiji" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Fiji</collectingCountry>
and therefore the 
<collectingCountry box="[151,188,1854,1878]" name="Fiji" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Fiji</collectingCountry>
<collectingCounty box="[192,324,1854,1878]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Archipelago</collectingCounty>
should be considered as the 
<typeStatus box="[624,670,1854,1878]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">type</typeStatus>
locality of the species. This could be taxonomically important if future genetic studies show that the two populations belong to separate species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,756,1438,2070]" lastBlockId="13.[831,1437,257,409]" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">
In one of our specimens (BFLA4006), some tentacle bulbs had atypical abaxial spurs formed by thickening of the exumbrellar epithelium (
<figureCitation box="[455,538,2046,2070]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="12.[151,186,1867,1889]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,258,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-7@12.[151,1436,258,1828]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Fig. 6. Merga violacea. (A-D) Specimen BFLA4006, bell height 12 mm. (A) Lateral view of whole animal, note that the bell is somewhat contracted and more elongate than normal. (B) Bell margin seen from oral, note the flat abaxial spurs above some of the tentacle bulbs (arrow). (C) Lateral view of stomach. (D) Bell margin, note rudimentary bulbs with short tentacle stumps. (E) Lateral view of younger animal observed 30-Jun-2018, size approximately 7 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5639954" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5639954/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
). Several specimens also had brown dots in the stomach wall (
<figureCitation box="[1301,1424,257,282]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="12.[151,186,1867,1889]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,258,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-7@12.[151,1436,258,1828]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Fig. 6. Merga violacea. (A-D) Specimen BFLA4006, bell height 12 mm. (A) Lateral view of whole animal, note that the bell is somewhat contracted and more elongate than normal. (B) Bell margin seen from oral, note the flat abaxial spurs above some of the tentacle bulbs (arrow). (C) Lateral view of stomach. (D) Bell margin, note rudimentary bulbs with short tentacle stumps. (E) Lateral view of younger animal observed 30-Jun-2018, size approximately 7 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5639954" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5639954/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Fig. 6A, C</figureCitation>
). There seem to be differences between Pacific and Atlantic individuals, including the colouration (comp. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bigelow" box="[831,990,353,377]" firstAuthor="Bigelow" pageId="13" pageNumber="249" pagination="1 - 243" refId="ref64854" refString="Bigelow H. B. 1909. The Medusae. Reports on the scientific results of the expedition to the eastern tropical Pacific, in charge of Alexander Agassiz, by the U. S. Fish Commission steamer &quot; Albatross &quot; from October, 1904, to March, 1905. XVI. Memoirs of the Museum of comparative Zoology at Harvard College 37: 1 - 243, pls 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="1909">Bigelow, 1909</bibRefCitation>
; or 
<bibRefCitation author="Schuchert" box="[1031,1208,353,377]" firstAuthor="Schuchert" pageId="13" pageNumber="249" refId="ref74770" refString="Schuchert P. 2020. World Hydrozoa Database. Accessed at http: // www. marinespecies. org / hydrozoa on 2020 - DEC- 11. DOI: 10.14284 / 357" type="book" year="2020">Schuchert, 2020</bibRefCitation>
: photos of Australian 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Agassiz &amp; Mayer" baseAuthorityYear="1899" box="[831,998,385,409]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Pandeidae" genus="Merga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="13" pageNumber="249" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="violacea">
<emphasis box="[831,998,385,409]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="249">Merga violacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
